.TH BROWSE-SQLITE3 1 "February 2026" "browse-sqlite3 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
browse-sqlite3 \- interactive terminal browser for SQLite databases
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B browse-sqlite3
.I database.db
.RI [ table ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B browse-sqlite3
is a full-screen terminal application for browsing and editing SQLite
databases. It provides three navigable views \(em a table list, a row
browser, and a per-field editor \(em with vi-style keyboard navigation,
readline-style inline editing, a Turbo Pascal\-inspired color scheme
using exact CGA palette values, and a context-sensitive help overlay.
.PP
If
.I table
is given, the browser opens directly to the row view for that table
(case-insensitive match).
.PP
Features include:
.IP \(bu 2
Vi-style navigation (hjkl, JK for paging, Tab to advance)
.IP \(bu 2
Readline-style inline field editor (^A/^E/^B/^F/^W/^K/^U/^T/^D/^G)
.IP \(bu 2
Unicode box-drawing characters with ASCII fallback
.IP \(bu 2
Turbo Pascal IDE colors via exact CGA RGB values when the terminal supports
.BR curses.can_change_color ()
.IP \(bu 2
Safety mode requiring confirmation before destructive actions
.IP \(bu 2
External editor and pager integration via
.B $EDITOR
and
.B $PAGER
.IP \(bu 2
East Asian wide-character display support
.IP \(bu 2
Smooth scrolling with batched key-repeat processing
.SH VIEWS
The interface has three views, navigated in a hierarchy:
.PP
.B "Table List"
\(-> (l/Right/Enter)
.B "Row Browser"
\(-> (l/Right/Enter)
.B "Field Editor"
.PP
Press
.B h
or
.B Left
to go back one level. Press
.B q
or
.B Esc
to quit from any view.
.SS Table List
Displays all tables in the database with their column names.
.TP
.BR j / Down
Move selection down
.TP
.BR k / Up
Move selection up
.TP
.BR J / PgDn
Page down
.TP
.BR K / PgUp
Page up
.TP
.B Tab
Next table
.TP
.BR l " / " Right " / " Enter
Open selected table in the row browser
.TP
.BR d " / " Del
Drop selected table (respects safety mode)
.TP
.B o
Set table display order (see
.BR ORDER )
.TP
.B f
Find/filter tables by name (see
.BR FIND )
.SS Row Browser
Displays all rows of the selected table in a columnar format.
.TP
.BR j / Down
Move selection down
.TP
.BR k / Up
Move selection up
.TP
.BR J / PgDn
Page down
.TP
.BR K / PgUp
Page up
.TP
.B Tab
Next row
.TP
.BR l " / " Right " / " Enter
Edit selected row in the field editor
.TP
.BR h " / " Left
Go back to table list
.TP
.BR d " / " Del
Delete selected row (respects safety mode)
.TP
.B Shift+Left
Scroll display left
.TP
.B Shift+Right
Scroll display right
.TP
.B o
Sort rows by column(s) (see
.BR ORDER )
.TP
.B f
Find/filter rows (see
.BR FIND )
.SS Field Editor
Displays each column of the selected row as a labeled field.
Fields whose values are too long for the screen are shown truncated
with a
.B [LONG]
indicator.
.TP
.BR j / Down
Move to next field
.TP
.BR k / Up
Move to previous field
.TP
.BR J / PgDn
Page down through fields
.TP
.BR K / PgUp
Page up through fields
.TP
.B Tab
Next field
.TP
.BR Enter " / " v
View field contents in pager
.TP
.BR l " / " Right
View in pager (only when field is truncated)
.TP
.B e
Edit field with the inline editor
.TP
.B E
Edit field in external editor ($EDITOR)
.TP
.BR h " / " Left
Go back to row browser (prompts if unsaved changes)
.TP
.BR d " / " Del
Set field to NULL (respects safety mode)
.TP
.B s
Save all changes to database
.TP
.B o
Set column display order (see
.BR ORDER )
.TP
.B f
Find/highlight fields (see
.BR FIND )
.SH INLINE EDITOR
When editing a field with
.BR e ,
a readline-compatible inline editor appears on the selected field's
line. If the value contains newlines or exceeds the available width,
the external editor is launched instead.
.SS Cursor Movement
.TP
.BR Left " / " ^B
Move cursor left
.TP
.BR Right " / " ^F
Move cursor right
.TP
.B ^A
Jump to beginning of line
.TP
.B ^E
Jump to end of line
.SS Editing
.TP
.B Backspace
Delete character before cursor
.TP
.BR Del " / " ^D
Delete character at cursor
.TP
.B ^W
Delete word backward
.TP
.B ^K
Kill to end of line
.TP
.B ^U
Kill to beginning of line
.TP
.B ^T
Transpose characters at cursor
.TP
.B ^L
Redraw screen
.SS Finishing
.TP
.B Enter
Save changes and stop editing
.TP
.B Tab
Save changes and advance to next field
.TP
.BR Esc " / " ^G
Abort edit, discarding changes to this field
.TP
.B ^C
Quit program immediately
.SH GLOBAL KEYS
These keys work in all views (except during inline editing):
.TP
.BR q " / " Esc
Quit program without saving
.TP
.B ^C
Quit program without saving
.TP
.B F1
Toggle context-sensitive help overlay
.TP
.B :
Enter command mode
.SH COMMAND MODE
Press
.B :
to enter command mode (vi-style). Available commands:
.TP
.B :safe
Enable safety mode (default). Destructive actions (dropping tables,
deleting rows, setting fields to NULL) require a y/n confirmation
prompt before proceeding.
.TP
.B :unsafe
Disable safety mode. Destructive actions take effect immediately
without confirmation.
.SH ORDER
Press
.B o
in any view to open the order/sort overlay. Its behavior depends on
the current view:
.SS Table List: Display Order
Rearranges the order in which tables appear.
Select a table with
.BR j / k ,
press
.B Space
to grab it, move it with
.BR j / k ,
then press
.B Space
again to drop it. The new order is persisted in the database
(in the
.B _browse_config
table) and restored on next launch.
.PP
This is analogous to rearranging entries in a directory listing.
The concept traces back to the ability of early file managers (such as
.BR mc (1))
to present items in a user-chosen sequence rather than the default
filesystem order.
.SS Row Browser: Sort by Column
Toggles multi-column sort on the current table's rows.
Press
.B Space
on a column name to add it to the sort order (or remove it),
.B a
for ascending,
.B d
for descending. When a column is active, grab it with
.B Space
and move with
.BR j / k
to change sort priority. The sort specification is persisted
per-table.
.PP
Multi-column sort follows the SQL
.B "ORDER BY"
convention: the first column is the primary key, subsequent columns
break ties. This mirrors
.BR sort (1)
with multiple
.B \-k
keys and the relational algebra ordering operators from
Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model.
.SS Field Editor: Column Order
Rearranges the display order of columns within a table.
Grab and move columns exactly as with table ordering.
The new column order is persisted per-table and affects both
the row browser and field editor displays.
.PP
Press
.B Esc
to close the overlay.
.SH FIND
Press
.B f
in any view to open the find bar at the bottom of the screen.
Type a search pattern and press
.BR Enter .
Press
.B Esc
to cancel.
.SS Table List
Plain substring match against table names; non-matching tables
are hidden from the list.
.SS Row Browser
The find bar accepts structured search patterns that are translated
into SQL
.B WHERE
clauses:
.TP
.I text
Free-text search. Matches any column containing the text
(becomes
.BR "col1 LIKE '%text%' OR col2 LIKE ..." ).
.TP
.IB col = val
Exact match on a named column
(becomes
.BR "col = 'val'" ).
.TP
.IB col ~ val
Substring (LIKE) match on a named column
(becomes
.BR "col LIKE '%val%'" ).
.PP
Multiple terms separated by spaces are ANDed together.
Column names available for filtering are shown as a hint line
above the find bar. An empty pattern or
.B .
clears the active filter.
.PP
This pattern language draws from the Unix tradition of composing
simple text-matching primitives.
The free-text search corresponds to
.BR grep (1)
across all fields; the
.IB col = val
syntax echoes
.BR awk (1)
field-matching expressions; and the
.IB col ~ val
form mirrors the
.B ~
match operator in
.BR awk .
The AND composition of space-separated terms follows the convention
established by
.BR grep (1)
pipelines, where multiple filters are chained
to narrow results.
.SS Field Editor
Plain substring match against column names and field values;
matching fields are highlighted.
.SS History
The find bar maintains a per-session history of search strings.
Press
.B Up
or
.B ^P
to recall previous searches, and
.B Down
or
.B ^N
to move forward through history. This follows the readline
history model used by
.BR bash (1)
and
.BR ftp (1).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B EDITOR
External editor for field editing (default:
.BR vi ).
When the editor name contains "vi", the editor is opened with the
cursor at the end of the file in insert mode.
.TP
.B PAGER
Pager for viewing field contents (default:
.BR less ", falling back to"
.BR more ).
.SH COLORS
.B browse-sqlite3
uses a color scheme inspired by the Turbo Pascal IDE. On terminals
that support
.BR curses.can_change_color ()
(such as those implementing the kitty graphics protocol), exact CGA
palette RGB values are programmed into color indices 16\-22 to
faithfully reproduce the original appearance:
.PP
.RS
.nf
Black    #000000    Blue   #0000AA
Green    #00AA00    Cyan   #00AAAA
Red      #AA0000    Yellow #FFFF55
White    #FFFFFF
.fi
.RE
.PP
On terminals that do not support color redefinition, the standard
curses color constants are used as a fallback; the actual appearance
will depend on the terminal's theme.
.SH UNICODE
Box-drawing characters (\(lq\[u250C]\[u2500]\[u2510]\[u2502]\[u2514]\[u2518]\(rq) are used
for the help overlay when the locale encoding supports them;
otherwise ASCII
.RB ( +\-| )
is used. Similarly, the horizontal rule under the title bar uses
\[u2500] or
.BR \- .
.PP
East Asian wide characters are handled correctly in both display
and inline editing, with proper double-width accounting.
.SH NOTES
The program opens the database file read-write. Changes made via the
field editor's
.B s
(save) command, row deletion, and table drops are committed immediately
to the database.
.PP
The
.B rowid
pseudo-column is used internally for updates and deletes. Tables
without a rowid (e.g., WITHOUT ROWID tables) may not work correctly.
.SH AUTHORS
Written with assistance from Claude (Anthropic).
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sqlite3 (1),
.BR less (1),
.BR vi (1)
